posts.name: JamesCH95
posts.cooked:
Let’s talk about squishing foam. New bumper rules and even more changes mean we can now consider optimizing bumper construction for our robots. Several folks have been working on understanding these changes, testing materials like legal and some not-yet-legal options. Assembled bumper test sections should arrive soon.

Here are the ground rules for this effort:
- Treat this like interactive build threads. I’m happy to help accommodate reasonable requests for testing variations, answering questions, and driving the discussion based on audience interest.
- Testing and results will be spread across many posts to avoid overwhelming anyone and speed up distribution.
- We’ll focus on core materials, acknowledging the limits of time and resources.
- Only consider first-order effects. Solutions may apply broadly but won’t be perfect for everyone.
- Tools are calibrated for quick testing, prioritizing efficiency over perfection.
- Answers are generalizations, offering broad insights rather than tailored solutions.

Important posts include discussions on test setup, conventional noodle bumpers, solid noodle degradation, validation comparisons, composite foam, collision analysis, and deeper dives into bumpers and testing rounds.

Bug fix reminder: Processing code had issues converting grams to Newtons. Plots have been remade and reposted.

posts.name: JamesCH95
posts.cooked:
Test Setup involved comparing FRC noodles for use in building structures. AM noodles were tested against Amazon alternatives based on their density. Testing was conducted using a "texture analyzer," where solid and hollow noodles were placed on either side. The results showed significant differences in performance under various loads.

Materials were sampled at specific dimensions:
- Approximately 5 inches tall
- About 1.5 inches wide
- Roughly 2.5 inches deep

Each sample underwent compression testing:
1. Started at zero load
2. Recorded once the load cell reached 1 Newton
3. Compressed until 1332 Newtons was achieved
4. Returned to initial position

Samples were tested repeatedly to assess stability and degradation over time. All materials were evaluated across fresh, unused areas before and during repeated testing to ensure consistency and reliability. Footnotes provided additional context regarding the testing methodology and equipment used.

posts.name: JamesCH95
posts.cooked:
Conventional Solid vs Hollow Pool Noodles  
We tested solid vs hollow pool noodles, including items from AM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="AndyMark"></template>, Amazon, etc., which were originally designed as literal pool noodles. The tests revealed that both solid and hollow noodles absorb energy, with solid noodles being stiffer and absorbing more energy. Near the upper limit of displacement, both materials become "solid," with stiffer springs as the force-distance slope steepens. Testing repeatedly showed that solid noodles degrade steadily due to material wear.  

The curves' starting points indicate the degree of bumper crushing, with damaged materials having less area under the curve. The biggest change occurred early, linked to cell popping in the noodles. Stay tuned for further developments.

posts.name: JamesCH95
posts.cooked:
I wonder if the degradation happens only at the most crushed end of the scale (80%+?) or if even repeated crush to say 50% depth results in degradation?

Comparing first to last in the repeat solid noodle test, and synchronizing the start position (rather than the maximum load position) we see that the degraded noodle is both softer at lower displacements and stiffer at high displacements. E.g. worse across the board.

Plotting with peak load synchronized we see that the degraded noodle has taken a set on the order of 6mm based on the difference in start positions.

After writing that out I think I understand your actual question. To answer that: it doesn’t take much load to start popping cells. Most people can grab a noodle and pop cells under very low loads.

It is not weird. The tested material is damaged, the cells certainly pop. The un-tested material right next to it is much less damaged (or not at all) and recovers more completely.

That’s because of the space left from from the counterbored bolt (that is facing down). The very center where the c’bore is does not get squished quite as much as the rest of the material.

posts.name: Mr. Steele
posts.cooked:
I love this thread! Thank you so much to 95 for getting a setup like this to help the larger FRC community. I look forward to seeing the results!

I’ve seen some teams experimenting with using either TPU-printed corners or a corner backer made from PVC pipe cut into 3/4-inch curves. I am wondering if there are plans for testing such a setup, if that’s even doable on the device you’ve calibrated.

For the backer rods, you mentioned more permanent deformation in the hollow pool noodles. Which of the two seems to have more overall impact absorption? I hope I’m reading these graphs correctly—I’m an amateur relative to the MatSci field. Personally, I’d prefer to damage a noodle via proximity to 2056 and replace between tournaments rather than have a less-damaged bumper but it absorbs less of the impact.

posts.name: Patrick
posts.cooked: Solid noodles have demonstrated increased durability compared to earlier assessments, based on data from the bumper task force and recent posts by James. However, solid noodles and the materials tested so far do not match the durability of EVA or crosslinked polyethylene. Efforts to test these alternatives will continue shortly.
